    "posts": [
      {
        "id": 258586,
        "name": "Junkyard Heroics",
        "username": "junkyardheroics",
        "avatar_template": "/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/j/e95f7d/{size}.png",
        "created_at": "2025-01-10T02:14:14.535Z",
        "cooked": "<p>Signal apps include several warnings that read like intentional scare warnings related to usernames, qr codes, and links. Specifically:</p>\n<ol>\n<li>“Only share your username with people you trust”</li>\n<li>“Only share your qr code and link with people you trust”</li>\n</ol>\n<p>To me, this reads as implying that there is a security/trust implication to sharing your username, QR, or link. As I understand it, the only actual implication to this is that someone who has your link or QR code knows your username. It’s not clear at all why the message “Only share your username with people you trust”. Shouldn’t it just be “People with your username can submit message requests”?</p>\n<p>Or, alternatively, if there <em>is</em> some security/trust implication to sharing this information, the actual consequences of it should really be spelled out better.</p>",
        "post_number": 1,
        "post_type": 1,
        "posts_count": 4,
        "updated_at": "2025-01-10T02:14:14.535Z",
